<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 93-12-09 - Horton Fan Clutch "System Saver"</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi931209" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>93-12-09</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>November, 1993</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>ENGINE</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Horton Fan Clutch "System Saver"</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <vendorgroup/>

                <vendor>Horton</vendor>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>Beginning September 1, 1993, Navistar started phasing in an improved version of the on/off air
                    driven Horton fan clutch. Eventually, all International vehicles ordered with an air driven on/off
                    Horton fan clutch will have the improved design. While the new and old clutches are interchangeable,
                    the updated version's Piston Friction Disc is equipped with a "System Saver" feature. The "System
                    Saver" performs as a fuse by reacting to clutch system faults to prevent overheating. The "System
                    Saver" is located on the outer surface of the piston friction disc (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9312091">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9312091" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9312091.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Old and New Style Piston Friction Disc</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. "SYSTEM SAVER"</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. BALANCE WEIGHT</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>
                    <title>"SYSTEM SAVER" RELEASE</title>
                </para>
                <para>The "System Saver" feature improves the long-term durability of the on/off fan clutch. If low air
                    pressure occurs for any reason in the system, the piston friction disc will begin to slip. The
                    friction of this slippage will create heat which will cause the "System Saver" to react, releasing
                    the clutch to prevent damage. The "System Saver" is fitted to the piston friction disc in a 1/8
                    inch, left-hand thread pipe plug (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9312091">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                    <emph type="bold">DO NOT ATTEMPT TO REPLACE THE "SYSTEM SAVER" WITH A NORMAL PIPE PLUG. THIS WILL
                        CAUSE THE CLUTCH TO BE OUT OF BALANCE, CREATING FURTHER ADVERSE CONDITIONS.
                    </emph>
                </para>
                <para>The "System Saver" must be replaced after it has released the clutch. The replacement part number
                    is 1694987-C1 and is available in the Navistar Parts Distribution System.
                </para>
                <para>A "System Saver" clutch release is detectable when the engine is shut down because the sound of
                    releasing air will be heard for a short time after the engine is turned off (see
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t9312091">Troubleshooting</hotlnk>Section). The rush of air at the front of the
                    piston friction disc is the primary indicator that the "System Saver" has released the clutch.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <warning>
                        <para>To avoid possible personal injury, do not check for this air rush or any air leak unless
                            the ignition switch is in the OFF position and the engine is stopped.
                        </para>
                    </warning>
                </specpara>
                <para>When the "System Saver" has released the clutch and shut down the system, the entire clutch
                    application system must be checked for air leaks, including clutch seals and air cartridge (Refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t9312091">Troubleshooting</hotlnk>). Also, the electrical control switches and
                    solenoid valve need to be tested for proper function. Any fan obstructions must be removed, and the
                    hub must turn freely when not engaged. THE CAUSE OF CLUTCH SLIPPAGE MUST BE DETERMINED AND REPAIRED
                    BEFORE THE CLUTCH IS PUT BACK INTO OPERATION. DO NOT REPLACE THE "SYSTEM SAVER" WITHOUT DETERMINING
                    THE CAUSE OF ITS RELEASE. As with the old fan clutch, "come home" bolts can be used to lock the
                    clutch temporarily until repairs can be made.
                </para>
                <table id="t9312091" frame="all">
                    <title>Troubleshooting Table</title>
                    <tgroup cols="3" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
                        <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.83in"/>
                        <colspec colwidth="2.43in"/>
                        <colspec colname="col3" colwidth="2.50in"/>
                        <spanspec namest="col1" nameend="col3" spanname="1to3"/>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Condition</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Possible Cause</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Remedy</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Air Leaking From Fan Clutch</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Bleed hole.</para>
                                    <para>2. Air chamber.</para>
                                    <para>3. Come home holes.</para>
                                    <para>4. "System Saver."</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>See
                                        <hotlnk xrefid="f9312092">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Bad face seal or air cartridge.</para>
                                    <para>2. Bad O-ring seals.</para>
                                    <para>3. Bad O-ring seals.</para>
                                    <para>4. See "System Saver" Release.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Install new seal kit.</para>
                                    <para>2. Install new seal kit.</para>
                                    <para>3. Install new seal kit.</para>
                                    <para>4. See "System Saver" Release.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Fails To Engage</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Electrical</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Broken circuit. (normally open system).</para>
                                    <para>2. Improperly wired.</para>
                                    <para>3. Thermal switch incorrect (for application) or defective.</para>
                                    <para>4. Bad solenoid valve.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Check electrical connection.</para>
                                    <para>2. Check wiring diagram.</para>
                                    <para>3. Check thermal switch application. Replace if wrong or defective.</para>
                                    <para>4. Replace solenoid valve.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Fails To Engage (Cont.)</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Air</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Clutch leaking.</para>
                                    <para>2. Air supply to clutch restricted.</para>
                                    <para>3. Solenoid valve defective.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Install new seal kit.</para>
                                    <para>2. Check fittings and air lines for leaks or pinching.</para>
                                    <para>3. Replace solenoid valve.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Fails To Disengage</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Electrical</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Broken current (normally closed system).</para>
                                    <para>2. Improperly wired.</para>
                                    <para>3. Thermal switch incorrect (for application) or defective.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Check electrical connections.</para>
                                    <para>2. Check wiring diagram.</para>
                                    <para>3. Check thermal switch application. Replace if wrong or defective.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry rowsep="0" valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Fails To Disengage (Cont.)</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Air</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Air line restricted, not allowing air to be released from fan clutch.
                                    </para>
                                    <para>2. Solenoid valve not exhausting.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Check for pinching or plugging of air line between clutch and valve.</para>
                                    <para>2. Check for plugged exhaust port. Clean port or replace valve.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Fails To Disengage (Cont.)</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Piston Friction Disc (PFD) Will Not Return</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Possibly seized due to contamination or worn splines.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Replace PFD and clean the air supply.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Cycles Frequently</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Electrical</emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Poor ground or wire connection.</para>
                                    <para>2. Improper temperature control settings.</para>
                                    <para>3. A/C Pressure Switch setting too low.</para>
                                    <para>4. Restriction in front of radiator, blocking air flow.</para>
                                    <para>5. Faulty thermal switch.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Check electrical connections.</para>
                                    <para>2. Check temperature settings of all controls. The thermal switch should
                                        engage the clutch 10 degrees higher than the shutter sensor.
                                    </para>
                                    <para>3. Check A/C Pressure Switch. Use higher switch.</para>
                                    <para>4. Check shutter operation, winter fronts or obstructions in front of
                                        radiator.
                                    </para>
                                    <para>5. Replace thermal switch.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Fan Clutch Engaged, Engine Running Hot</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Restriction in front of radiator.</para>
                                    <para>2. Fan capacity not large enough.</para>
                                    <para>3. Problem in cooling system.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Make sure nothing is obstructing the air flow through the radiator.</para>
                                    <para>2. Refer to manufacturers specifications.</para>
                                    <para>3. Refer to engine manual.</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">"System Saver" will release engagement when clutch slips
                                            excessively causing abnormal heat build-up:
                                        </emph>
                                    </para>
                                    <para>1. Obstructed fan.</para>
                                    <para>2. Low air pressure to clutch.</para>
                                    <para>3. Excessive cycling.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Loose shroud, bent fan, torn engine mounts, etc.</para>
                                    <para>2.</para>
                                    <para>A. Restricted air line.</para>
                                    <para>B. Restricted solenoid.</para>
                                    <para>C. Low system air pressure.</para>
                                    <para>3.</para>
                                    <para>A. A/C freon overcharge.</para>
                                    <para>B. A/C pressure setting too low.</para>
                                    <para>C. Poor ground or wire connection.</para>
                                    <para>D. Improper temperature control setting.</para>
                                    <para>E. Faulty thermal switch.</para>
                                    <para>F. Restriction in front of radiator blocking air flow.</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top">
                                    <para>1. Find and remove obstruction. Repair or replace damaged parts.*</para>
                                    <para>2.</para>
                                    <para>A. Replace air line.</para>
                                    <para>B. Replace solenoid.</para>
                                    <para>C. Determine cause and repair.</para>
                                    <para>3.</para>
                                    <para>A. Check and adjust to specifications.</para>
                                    <para>B. Check A/C switch.</para>
                                    <para>C. Check electrical connection.</para>
                                    <para>D. Check temperature setting of all controls. Thermal switch setting should
                                        engage the clutch 10&#176;F higher than the full open temperature of the
                                        thermostat.
                                    </para>
                                    <para>E. Replace thermal switch.</para>
                                    <para>F. Check for proper shutter operation, winter front or other restriction in or
                                        in front of radiator.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="3" spanname="1to3" valign="top">
                                    <para>*Air cartridge must be checked to assure the carbon tip springs back easily
                                        when depressed. If carbon tip does not spring back, the CARTRIDGE AND HUB
                                        BEARING
                                        <emph type="bold">MUST</emph>
                                        be replaced as a set.
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
